04257nam a22006615i 9780226553061DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2018    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802265530617 a10.7208/97802265530612doi  a(DE-B1597)523461  a(OCoLC)1046065802  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aB1247 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a320.012231 aStauffer, Devin, eauthor.10aHobbes's Kingdom of Light :bA Study of the Foundations of Modern Political Philosophy /cDevin Stauffer. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b1 halftone  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tEditions and Abbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1. "Of Darkness from Vain Philosophy" -- t2. Hobbes's Natural Philosophy -- t3. Religion and Theology I: "Of Religion" -- t4. Religion and Theology II: Hobbes's Natural Theology -- t5. Religion and Theology III: Hobbes's Confrontation with the Bible -- t6. Hobbes's Political Philosophy I: Man and Morality -- t7. Hobbes's Political Philosophy II: The Hobbesian Commonwealth -- tAppendix. The Engraved Title Page of Leviathan -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWas Hobbes the first great architect of modern political philosophy? Highly critical of the classical tradition in philosophy, particularly Aristotle, Hobbes thought that he had established a new science of morality and politics. Devin Stauffer here delves into Hobbes's critique of the classical tradition, making this oft-neglected aspect of the philosopher's thought the basis of a new, comprehensive interpretation of his political philosophy. In Hobbes's Kingdom of Light, Stauffer argues that Hobbes was engaged in a struggle on multiple fronts against forces, both philosophic and religious, that he thought had long distorted philosophy and destroyed the prospects of a lasting peace in politics. By exploring the twists and turns of Hobbes's arguments, not only in his famous Leviathan but throughout his corpus, Stauffer uncovers the details of Hobbes's critique of an older outlook, rooted in classical philosophy and Christian theology, and reveals the complexity of Hobbes's war against the "Kingdom of Darkness." He also describes the key features of the new outlook-the "Kingdom of Light"-that Hobbes sought to put in its place. Hobbes's venture helped to prepare the way for the later emergence of modern liberalism and modern secularism. Hobbes's Kingdom of Light is a wide-ranging and ambitious exploration of Hobbes's thought.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aChurch and state. 0aPolitical sciencexHistoryy17th century. 4aHobbes. 4aKingdom of Darkness. 4aKingdom of Light. 4aLeviathan. 4aclassical philosophy. 4acritique of religion. 4aliberalism. 4amorality. 4anatural philosophy. 4aphilosophy. 4apolitical philosophy. 4apolitics. 4areligion. 4asecularism. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226553061423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226553061.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles